00:00:51.279 --> 00:00:55.880
how that is very deeply connected to the R community.

00:00:55.880 --> 00:01:03.240
So in the tradition of putting Hadley on a slide, I was working in a database architectures

00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:08.839
research group back in Amsterdam a couple of years ago, and we realized that data scientists

00:01:08.839 --> 00:01:14.480
and specifically our users really hated data management systems, and it hurt our feelings

00:01:14.480 --> 00:01:15.480
a little bit.

00:01:15.480 --> 00:01:20.739
So here's a quote from Hadley, if your data fits in memory, there is no advantage of putting

00:01:20.739 --> 00:01:26.059
into a database, it will only be slower and more frustrating.

00:01:26.059 --> 00:01:27.660
Okay.

00:01:27.660 --> 00:01:34.300
And we thought very much about that, and we realized that he was right.

00:01:34.300 --> 00:01:35.580
Databases can be very frustrating.

00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:42.940
So here we have sort of the good and the bad bandits here, and they can be very bad.

00:01:42.940 --> 00:01:45.019
Setting up databases is very difficult.

00:01:45.860 --> 00:01:51.860
Even for somebody who has a PhD in data management systems, setting up Postgres is a daunting

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:53.980
task sometimes.

00:01:53.980 --> 00:01:56.459
Seriously.

00:01:56.459 --> 00:02:00.019
And I have seriously, I've set up so many systems over the years because, you know,

00:02:00.019 --> 00:02:04.860
you need to run experiments and so on and so forth, and my favorite one, I think, like

00:02:04.860 --> 00:02:10.139
a little anecdote, you cannot literally install IBM DB2 and Oracle on the same machine.

00:02:10.139 --> 00:02:11.139
It's just not possible.

00:02:11.139 --> 00:02:13.539
But of course, you know, it took me a week to realize this.

00:02:13.660 --> 00:02:14.660
Installation.

00:02:14.660 --> 00:02:15.660
Maintenance.

00:02:15.660 --> 00:02:16.660
Yeah.

00:02:16.660 --> 00:02:20.139
So then once you have installed this thing, you need to somehow make sure it runs, you

00:02:20.139 --> 00:02:24.300
know, we have to deal with user accounts, all that stuff, you have to update, all not

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:25.779
very pretty.

00:02:25.779 --> 00:02:31.139
And something that really came out when we worked with data people is the data transfer.

00:02:31.139 --> 00:02:36.899
In fact, we wrote a paper about how slow transfer back and forth from databases is.

00:02:36.899 --> 00:02:40.899
You would actually not believe that if you're not starting to run experiments in it, even

00:02:40.899 --> 00:02:45.580
for something like Spark, you know, that uses just ancient protocols, it's not a great

00:02:45.580 --> 00:02:46.580
user experience.

00:02:46.580 --> 00:02:48.619
So that's bad.

00:02:48.619 --> 00:02:50.380
There is also good things in databases.

00:02:50.380 --> 00:02:54.899
For example, you know, the, I don't know, 40 or so years, no, actually at this point

00:02:54.899 --> 00:02:59.179
it's 50 years since relational databases have existed.

00:02:59.179 --> 00:03:03.419
We have spent a lot of time on optimizing queries so that the user doesn't have to actually

00:03:03.419 --> 00:03:07.740
become a database engine in their head and start, you know, reshuffling things in order

00:03:07.740 --> 00:03:08.740
to make them faster.

00:03:08.740 --> 00:03:11.100
It should be automatic.

00:03:11.100 --> 00:03:12.100
Persistence, right?

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:16.500
The original motivation of making data management systems was to get rid of these file zoos

00:03:16.500 --> 00:03:21.259
that people write like, you know, custom programs to operate on to make some changes to set

00:03:21.259 --> 00:03:28.220
files and instead have sort of a defined transactional persistence model with updates and consistency.

00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:31.380
That's quite useful.

00:03:31.380 --> 00:03:36.259
And of course, most notably, especially in my community of analytical data management

00:03:36.259 --> 00:03:40.860
systems, we have spent a lot of time working on efficiency and parallelism.

00:03:40.860 --> 00:03:45.020
But the problem was that the frustrating bits were kind of hiding the good stuff.

00:03:45.020 --> 00:03:49.419
And the good way of looking at this was that people have been sort of ignoring the sandwich

00:03:49.419 --> 00:03:52.139
principle as I like to call it.

00:03:52.139 --> 00:03:56.100
People have spent a lot of time optimizing like the patty, whether it's vegetarian or

00:03:56.100 --> 00:03:58.699
not is up to you.

00:03:58.699 --> 00:04:02.699
Optimizing that till the end of the world, like there is hundreds of papers on how to

00:04:02.699 --> 00:04:08.380
optimize a join, but we've literally wrote the first paper on optimizing client protocols,

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:09.380
right?

00:04:09.380 --> 00:04:12.580
Nobody has ever looked at the user end-to-end user experience.

00:04:12.580 --> 00:04:16.540
And I think that's why people perceive these things as to be frustrating and would actually

00:04:16.540 --> 00:04:19.899
rather invent their own than to touch that stuff.

00:04:19.899 --> 00:04:22.899
So in comes DuckDB.

00:04:22.899 --> 00:04:29.100
So we wrote a new data management system from scratch together with my former PhD student

00:04:29.100 --> 00:04:34.980
Mark Rasfeld that has basically tried to fix this end-to-end user experience.

00:04:34.980 --> 00:04:37.140
So it's in process.

00:04:37.140 --> 00:04:42.959
I will explain to you in a bit what that means just so that you can have a better user experience.

00:04:42.959 --> 00:04:49.700
It is still, despite focusing on the end-to-end, a state-of-the-art data execution engine that

00:04:49.700 --> 00:04:54.859
can, you know, really go through data in a very, very quick way.

00:04:54.859 --> 00:04:56.820
And the best part, it's free and open source.

00:04:56.820 --> 00:04:57.820
So you can just use it.

00:04:57.820 --> 00:04:59.179
It's not MIT-licensed.

00:04:59.179 --> 00:05:01.779
I always say, you know, go build a company on it.

00:05:01.779 --> 00:05:04.059
I'm going to be happy about it.

00:05:04.059 --> 00:05:05.380
First question, why is it called DuckDB?

00:05:05.380 --> 00:05:08.220
It's because I used to have a duck.

00:05:08.220 --> 00:05:09.220
Okay.

00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:11.500
It's true.

00:05:11.500 --> 00:05:12.500
What can I say?

00:05:12.500 --> 00:05:13.500
Okay.

00:05:13.500 --> 00:05:18.179
So let me go a bit about sort of the design philosophy of DuckDB.

00:05:18.179 --> 00:05:20.220
The first is it should be simple, right?

00:05:20.220 --> 00:05:25.140
Like we shouldn't have to have a PhD in databases not to set this thing up.

00:05:25.299 --> 00:05:27.980
And it also shouldn't be, you know, like hard to use.

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:33.700
So one thing we noticed is that a database that a lot of people are quite comfortable

00:05:33.700 --> 00:05:35.019
with is SQLite.

00:05:35.019 --> 00:05:37.059
And why is SQLite so easy to use?

00:05:37.059 --> 00:05:42.540
Well, because it's in process, which means that the database system actually runs directly

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:44.160
to whichever process you link to.

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:49.260
So in R, you have Kirill's rsqlite package that you can just like load and then you can

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:51.739
just run SQLite without any external setup.

00:05:51.739 --> 00:05:52.959
Isn't that great?

00:05:52.959 --> 00:05:54.679
So we copied that idea for DuckDB.

00:05:54.679 --> 00:06:01.320
DuckDB runs fully in process, which also has some really great benefits for data transfer,

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:07.000
one of the other frustrations that I will talk to you in a bit about.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:09.760
DuckDB doesn't have dependencies.

00:06:09.760 --> 00:06:17.119
So we just have a giant blob of C++ code that, well, yeah, that you can just install with

00:06:17.119 --> 00:06:18.619
install.packages, right?

00:06:18.619 --> 00:06:25.220
It doesn't have external dependencies besides DBI and R. In Python, it works, I said the

00:06:25.220 --> 00:06:26.940
P word, it works the same way.

00:06:26.940 --> 00:06:33.220
You can just install DuckDB as a package and it will just run.

00:06:33.220 --> 00:06:38.799
But again, you shouldn't be fooled by it being simple by taking it as simplistic or sort

00:06:38.799 --> 00:06:43.380
of, you know, limited in terms of what the engine can do.

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:48.059
So as I mentioned, we have transactions, we have persistence, we have extensive relational

00:06:48.500 --> 00:06:52.459
features like, you know, complex joins, aggregates, window functions.

00:06:52.459 --> 00:06:57.019
DuckDB can read and write parquet files out of the box, CSV files, JSON file, all in parallel.

00:06:57.019 --> 00:07:02.019
It's really quite fully featured.

00:07:02.019 --> 00:07:06.579
DuckDB is very fast, too, and, you know, I know everybody says this, but this is not

00:07:06.579 --> 00:07:09.779
just like, oh, we've run a benchmark and it was fast.

00:07:09.779 --> 00:07:12.339
But the people always ask me, why is it fast?

00:07:12.339 --> 00:07:13.420
What do you do?

00:07:13.420 --> 00:07:15.899
And then it's sometimes very difficult to explain.

00:07:15.899 --> 00:07:21.579
So I asked the team what I should say and I said, just say it's magic.

00:07:21.579 --> 00:07:28.160
Of course, any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from magic, as you know.

00:07:28.160 --> 00:07:29.380
So what is the magic here?

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:33.779
The magic is that it's the culmination of decades of research in analytical data management

00:07:33.779 --> 00:07:34.779
systems.

00:07:34.779 --> 00:07:40.500
Literally, tens of PhDs went into the basic concepts that we basically implemented at

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:41.500
DuckDB.

00:07:41.500 --> 00:07:44.700
Some of it in our own group in the database research group in Amsterdam, some from other

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:45.779
groups.

00:07:45.859 --> 00:07:47.820
But it really is this culmination.

00:07:47.820 --> 00:07:50.179
How does this sort of show itself?

00:07:50.179 --> 00:07:55.579
Well, one of the advantages of DuckDB, and that makes it really fast, is that it can

00:07:55.579 --> 00:08:03.859
automatically paralyze very complex SQL queries over all the available CPU cores.

00:08:03.859 --> 00:08:07.220
But the problem is that this also, Spark can also do this.

00:08:07.220 --> 00:08:12.299
But the problem is, in order to get good utilization, it's not enough to just blindly paralyze.

00:08:12.299 --> 00:08:16.220
You also have to get a good efficiency on a per-core level, and DuckDB is also really

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:22.380
good at that with highly efficient C++ code.

00:08:22.380 --> 00:08:26.700
For example, it can also use the disk if there's not enough RAM available to complete a query,

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:29.500
so we can go out of core on all the operators.

00:08:29.500 --> 00:08:34.780
And this all happens completely sort of automatically, transparently to the user.

00:08:34.780 --> 00:08:36.900
So you just type your query and go off.

00:08:36.900 --> 00:08:39.820
One thing that you can sort of notice when you're on DuckDB that your laptop might get

00:08:39.820 --> 00:08:42.260
a bit warm, right?

00:08:42.260 --> 00:08:46.460
That's just, it's a bit of a downside sometimes if it's hot outside, I don't know.

00:08:46.460 --> 00:08:53.739
Yeah, and I mentioned DuckDB is free, so it's just, you know, choose all four.

00:08:53.739 --> 00:08:58.539
A bit about R, since everybody here loves R, DuckDB loves R as well.

00:08:58.539 --> 00:09:04.780
In fact, the whole idea of creating a new database management system came out of the

00:09:04.780 --> 00:09:10.059
interactions with the R community, and I want to mention Thomas Loomley and Anthony D'Amico,

00:09:10.059 --> 00:09:15.260
maybe some of you know them, who really pushed us because we were working with them as a

00:09:15.260 --> 00:09:17.820
sort of, why do you hate us so much?

00:09:17.820 --> 00:09:21.700
And then, you know, we came up with solutions and they said, yeah, it is better, but still

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:22.700
not good enough.

00:09:22.700 --> 00:09:27.380
And, you know, we went back to our little, you know, love and continued and continued.

00:09:27.380 --> 00:09:28.659
And this was really productive.

00:09:28.659 --> 00:09:30.299
It went on for many years.

00:09:30.299 --> 00:09:34.820
And in the end, it was really clear what needed to happen and also how to deeply integrate

00:09:34.820 --> 00:09:38.979
that into R. We also worked a lot with R core on, for example,

00:09:38.979 --> 00:09:43.859
the entire Altrep framework so we could do more clever things with DuckDB in connections

00:09:43.859 --> 00:09:47.460
with R. So one thing that's really clever that came

00:09:47.460 --> 00:09:51.299
out of this is that DuckDB runs in process.

00:09:51.299 --> 00:09:58.059
In R, it runs in the same process as, like, the R interpreter itself, okay?

00:09:58.059 --> 00:10:00.440
That sounds a bit technical, I realize that.

00:10:00.440 --> 00:10:05.380
But one big advantage of that is that because we run in the same process, we can actually

00:10:05.380 --> 00:10:10.580
look at the data frames that exist in the R process itself.

00:10:10.580 --> 00:10:15.219
So if you want to just run a query on a data frame, we don't have to sort of go through,

00:10:15.219 --> 00:10:19.500
like, some serialization, write a 2-part GIF file, read it again, I don't know.

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:25.059
We can just look directly at the memory and say, hey, this looks like some bits from a

00:10:25.059 --> 00:10:26.419
data frame.

00:10:26.419 --> 00:10:30.659
Maybe we can just make that look like a table and then you can run queries on it.

00:10:30.659 --> 00:10:37.340
And similarly, the query results in DuckDB can directly become R data frames in the same

00:10:37.340 --> 00:10:40.419
process without having to go through IPC or anything like that, right?

00:10:40.419 --> 00:10:45.059
So we can basically say, you run a query, it has a million rows, results, which normally

00:10:45.059 --> 00:10:50.659
would be the end of the world in sort of traditional setup with client server.

00:10:50.659 --> 00:10:53.299
But with DuckDB, it's just like, whoop, okay, there you go.

00:10:53.299 --> 00:10:57.619
We even have some sort of tricks where sometimes we don't even have to transform the data,

00:10:57.619 --> 00:11:00.020
we can directly use the R structures.

00:11:00.460 --> 00:11:03.859
Again, saying the P word, of course, the same trick also works in Pandas.

00:11:03.859 --> 00:11:08.900
So if you have a Pandas data frame sitting there, that works as well.

00:11:08.900 --> 00:11:14.460
But now I'm going to sort of do the unimaginable and try a live demo.

